dan, Paddy.","Irish (Cork): because of the earlier Anglicized form <b>Houlton</b>, MacLysaght suggests this may be a variant of   Houlihan  .","English: possibly a variant of <b>Whelpton</b>, a habitational name perhaps from West Whelpington or Kirkwhelpington (Northumberland), with loss of the <i>-ing-</i>. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hwelp</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. There is scope for confusion with   Wheeldon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Houlihan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen.","Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUallacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uallachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>úallach</i> ‘proud, arrogant’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"titl